{
  "text": "The experiment was organized into four conditions presented to each participant in randomized order. Each condition consisted of a sexual or neutral film clip, a rating of subjective sexual arousal in response to the film clip, and a sexual or neutral go/no-go task. Each go/no-go task included 10 blocks of 10 trials depicting either all sexual or all neutral stimuli. Thus, the four conditions were as follows: a neutral film clip followed by a neutral go/no-go task (NF/NT), a neutral film clip followed by a sexual go/no-go task (NF/ST), a sexual film clip followed by a neutral go/no-go task (SF/NT), and a sexual film clip followed by a sexual go/no-go task (SF/ST; see Table 1 ). All stimuli within each condition were presented in randomized order. As in [CITATION_1] , task contingencies were reversed halfway through each condition, such that previously correct stimuli (i.e., Go stimuli) were followed by feedback indicating a wrong response, and previously wrong stimuli (i.e., No-go stimuli) were followed by feedback indicating a correct response. Participants were not informed when this contingency reversal would occur.",
